I've done member, didn't really like it. I find it reads awkwardly. It's formal language that's practically extinct in the common vernacular. Manhood is better, precisely because its used more casually. I suppose this is where writing style comes in. If you write as a discernible narrator, you can take more liberty with language and descriptions. I tend to write more focused on the point of view of the main character (or the point of view character, rather), so I try to choose language that befits that point of view.

As for dialogue, that follows similar rules in respect to character. I try to have them say things you'd expect from the situation and their personality. For instance, nobody seriously says "fuck me harder with that sick cock, my dude", or even a more chaste variety of that. But she might say it ironically, or to get a rise out of her lover, at the appropriate moment (which isn't when he's ball-deep in her). Or she might yell it up to the sky after her totally rad VW van gets stolen.
